---
alwaysApply: true
---

Treat multiplayer state as an unreliable, delayed, eventually-consistent system. All features must be resilient to latency, duplication, and out-of-order updates.

Core Requirement

Every shared object (e.g., a pin) must have:

a unique, stable ID
a single authoritative data source
a deterministic way to reconstruct it on any client

If any of these are missing, the system will break under real conditions.

Execution Behavior
1. Always use IDs, never implicit objects

Do NOT rely on:

“the last object created”
scene hierarchy assumptions

Instead:

{
  id: string,
  position: vec3,
  ownerId: string
}

All sync logic must key off id.

2. Separate local intent from network state

When a user performs an action (e.g., drops a pin):

Immediately render locally (optimistic feedback)
Then send to RealtimeStore

Do NOT wait for the network to confirm before showing results.

3. Rebuild state from the network, not the scene

At any time, your agent should be able to:

clear all SceneObjects
rebuild everything from RealtimeStore

This ensures:

late joiners work
reconnection works
desyncs can recover
4. Handle out-of-order and duplicate updates

Assume:

updates can arrive late
updates can arrive twice
updates can overwrite newer data

Therefore:

Always check id before creating objects
Update existing objects instead of recreating
Prefer last-write-wins or timestamp logic if needed
5. Never sync transforms every frame

Do NOT:

stream continuous position updates per frame

Instead:

send discrete events:
“pin created”
“pin updated”
“pin removed”

Continuous sync will:

break performance
introduce jitter
overload the session
6. Treat RealtimeStore as the source of truth
SceneObjects = view layer only
RealtimeStore = actual state

If they disagree:
→ RealtimeStore wins

7. Handle join/leave explicitly

Your system must:

spawn all existing objects when a new user joins
avoid duplicating objects on rejoin
clean up or reassign ownership if a user leaves (if needed)

Use session lifecycle hooks for this.

8. Minimize payload size

Only sync what is necessary:

position
id
minimal metadata

Avoid:

large blobs
unnecessary updates
Hard Prohibitions
Do NOT rely on execution order between clients
Do NOT assume instant delivery
Do NOT bind logic directly to SceneObjects without data backing
Do NOT create objects without IDs
Do NOT treat multiplayer as “real-time perfect sync”
Guiding Principle

The network is eventually correct, not immediately correct.

Design so that:

temporary inconsistencies are acceptable
final state always converges
